                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Fading got it. The boggle thing wasn't the big one, it was the memblur thing that really got me. And, I know for a fact this guy has been up to PoH almost every night trying to get his EoV. There's absolutely no reason to use Bliss when Dazzle is all you need. There is a problem with dazzle, actually, and it's that is has a recast time associated with it. But if you're only looking at one add, (which the monk was doing a great job of doing, don't think we ever had more than 2 inc per pull the whole night) it's great. Half the mana cost of Bliss, 30 seconds (give or take) more duration. However, I will say that I know a lot of enchanters that always use bliss regardless. For myself, I use the lowest level mez I have to use. If mobs are 55 or below, dazzle, if I'm in high end Kunark (shrooms, juggs, etc) apathy or GoK. If I don't know the levels of the mobs, if they're blue or even, I use sleep (assuming PoP), if they're yellow or red, bliss.
<br />

<br />
And about the memblur thing, well, I suppose I can give him the benefit of the doubt about not using boggle because it may or may not work (personally, it's always worked great for me. If I get debuff agro, boggle will usually take agro off in one cast). But, being level 65 and having spells like AR at his disposal, he should know that being beat on by a relatively wussy (slowed!) mob is better than AEing everyone and having the mob ping ponged for the whole fight. He'd probably have atleast 3800hp, and hand doesn't hit that hard.
<br />

<br />
Something I didn't mention in my first post was that this guy is in my brother's guild, and he has a habit of getting groups or group members killed with memblur. He even got all the wizards killed on a BL epic fight using memblur. He's been asked countless times not to use it in the middle of the fight, but I guess he doesn't understand why people around him are dying.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I never have any hate reduction spells or gate up. in my opinon, it shows distrust in your group and your own abilities. And I don't have enough spell slots.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I haven't had gate memmed during a group since I was level 20. But the agro redux can be important. I like debuffing early, for example. If it means I take a few rounds and have to re-cast rune, that's fine. This is my style of play anyway. It has nothing to do with trust. When it's up, it's usually either because we have a warrior tank, or I'm on a raid, on a long fight like Cursed where my job is to stand at max range, and bomb the crap out of him. I'll twist boggles in to keep from getting agro between my nukes. Sure, I could wait to debuff, but what's the point if I have the mana to re-cast runes, and cast boggle? I don't make room for boggle specifically, but if there's an open slot, I'll usually toss it in there. It's nothing about distrust in myself or my group, it's all about utility and using the tools I have as an edge.
<br />

<br />
/derail off
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Maybe he simply didn't know? I know I've done a few stupid things in my chanter life I didn't realize were stupid until I grouped with another chanter. They politely sent me a tell saying "It would be easier on your mana, and your health if you did it this way"... and I learned I was doing something wrong and corrected it. Next time, try sending him a tell. =)
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Hehe, after he told me he doesn't know what boggle does, I told him exactly what it does, and his reply to me was along the lines of, "Yeah, but that doesn't get rid of all my agro." I told him that getting rid of some is much better than wiping the list completely. He disagreed with me. So, I asked him if he knew why the mob was being ping ponged and agro'd everyone. He said it was because THEY (as in the casters, etc) were over-agroing. Even though they didn't even nuke until around 75%...heh, more than enough time for the warrior to build sufficient agro. Also, see above where he's been told countless times not to blur. Oh, and imo, not knowing what a spell does is no longer a valid excuse in my eyes. Every spell has a description of it's general purpose. Granted, it doesn't tell you exactly what the spell does, but it gives you an idea.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><center>Sage Fadarm
